# Mojo Module Boundaries

Keep layers explicit as the repo grows. Adjust names to your tree; the rule is **direction of dependency**, not a specific folder spelling.

## Suggested layers

| Layer | Role | May import from |
|-------|------|-----------------|
| **kernel** | hot numeric/SIMD core, no I/O | stdlib, other kernel helpers |
| **domain** | types, invariants, pure logic | kernel (if needed), domain |
| **host** | CLI, orchestration, file/network | domain, kernel public API |
| **ffi** | Python/C ABI adapters | domain/kernel through narrow facades |
| **generated** | codegen output | nothing imports "up" into hand-written domain |

## Import rule

From outside a layer, import only through that layer's **public entry** (`__init__.mojo`, `public.mojo`, or documented `Main`-style module) — not deep internal files.

Inside a layer, submodules may import each other per local design.

## Do not

- Reach from kernel into host I/O or Python.
- Put wire decode (proto/JSON) inside SIMD inner loops — decode at boundary, pass typed values inward.
- Duplicate domain types at ffi boundary; convert once at the edge.

## When adding a check script

If the repo adds `make check-module-boundaries` or similar, update it when layer layout changes — same spirit as boundary checks in larger backends.
